European debt write-down is unavoidable
Berkeley — — “That was just the Greek crisis,” “That was just the crisis of Greece and Ireland,” people used to think, but now it's not like that anymore, because it's clearly a crisis of the eurozone.
Fighting it is both easier and harder than people usually think.
The economic logic of this crisis is quite simple.
Greece has a problem with its finances.
Ireland's banking sector has problems.
Portugal's private debt market has problems.
Spain has problems in all three areas.
Although the details are different, the conclusion is the same: all these countries will have to go through the painful process of spending cuts.
To offset the effects of austerity policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic spending cuts and currency devaluation.
Devaluation will enhance export competitiveness, which is to rely on foreign demand to make up for domestic demand.
However, these countries are all eurozone countries, and they do not have independent currencies that can be devalued, so they can only use internal devaluation to replace external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to enhance export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding foreign demand.
In fact, the determination of these crisis countries to tighten their belts is not small.
However, one economic variable has not changed with the adjustment of other variables, which is the debt of the public and private sectors.
The face value of government accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debt —— except for some debt owed to junior creditors —— has not changed either.
It is this simple fact that has put the internal devaluation strategy in a self-contradictory position: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending needs to be cut and taxes increased in order to pay off government and its creditors (such as banks) debt.
This, in turn, requires even more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, creating a vicious cycle that drags the economy into recession.
So, in order for the internal devaluation strategy to be effective, a way to reduce the debt value must be found.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity, and banks should be shut down when they are insolvent.
Mortgages must also be written down.
Policy makers are reluctant to take this path, which is understandable.
Contracts are sacred.
Government is worried about losing credibility with the financial market.
If creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, debt write-downs will only harm other countries.
These concerns are not unreasonable, but they should not lead to an unreasonable conclusion.
There are only two options: internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European leaders must choose one of them.
They have all ruled out the option of external devaluation.
But internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this point is neither logical nor reasonable.
The operation of debt restructuring is simple.
The government can issue a batch of bonds, the face value of which is discounted by a certain percentage from the existing debt face value.
Bondholders can choose either to hold onto their bonds and exchange them at face value, but with a later maturity date and lower interest rate; or accept a discounted bond with a lower face value than their current bond, but with an earlier maturity date and higher interest rate.
This is not some cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to succeed, there are three prerequisites.
First, you need to guarantee the safety of the new bonds to the bondholders.
You need someone to come forward and guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, when the Brady Plan was implemented to restructure Latin American debt, the U.S. Department of the Treasury played the role of "guarantor brother".
Today, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Secondly, all countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, a country's restructuring will increase expectations for other countries, triggering a contagion effect.
Finally, banks that suffer losses due to debt restructuring must consolidate their balance sheets.
These banks need to undergo a real stress test, rather than the PR exercise they underwent earlier this year.
If debt restructuring implies capital shortfalls, then a comprehensive debt-for-equity swap for all bank liabilities is necessary.
If this is not enough, the government must step in to inject capital into the banks.
This too requires a unified action from all countries.
Once the banks' balance sheets are consolidated, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debt without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires decisive leadership.
Germany's leaders must acknowledge that the country's banks have a large risk exposure to debt in peripheral eurozone countries, and the situation is critical.
They must convince the backroom bosses and voters that using public funds to provide guarantees for debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; since Germany is urging other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should not shy away from bearing the responsibility.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, need to make the consequences sound more severe – otherwise, a major disaster will strike.
Because that's the fact.
